{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/plugin-library-page-creator-a7319577b6a3c80ad18489a1bc6b3c72-e34da.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 786px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 77.25000000000001%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px #ffffff;\"\n        alt=\"Gatsby plugin page creator in the plugin library\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/plugin-library-page-creator-a7319577b6a3c80ad18489a1bc6b3c72-c4266.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/plugin-library-page-creator-a7319577b6a3c80ad18489a1bc6b3c72-4fd5b.png 197w,\n/static/plugin-library-page-creator-a7319577b6a3c80ad18489a1bc6b3c72-4fc86.png 393w,\n/static/plugin-library-page-creator-a7319577b6a3c80ad18489a1bc6b3c72-c4266.png 786w,\n/static/plugin-library-page-creator-a7319577b6a3c80ad18489a1bc6b3c72-22348.png 1179w,\n/static/plugin-library-page-creator-a7319577b6a3c80ad18489a1bc6b3c72-e34da.png 1200w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 786px) 100vw, 786px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>In this article we will talk about a new plugin that lets you auto create\npages from components in any folder within your Gatsby project! We will chat about the\nproblem that sparked the creation of this plugin. Afterwards, we’ll talk about how you can\nuse this plugin to auto create pages without having to place your components in the <strong>src/pages</strong> directory.</p>\n<h1 id=\"the-problem-with-static-values\"><a href=\"#the-problem-with-static-values\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>The problem with static values</h1>\n<p>Here’s how it all got started. The goal with <a href=\"https://gatsbymanor.com\">Gatsby Manor</a> (a separate project, unaffiliated with the Gatsby core team)\nis to create professional designed Gatsby starters\nto give your site a clean, modern look the moment you create a new project.\nWhile creating our newest starter\n<a href=\"https://gatsbymanor.com/demo/eventually\">gatsby-starter-eventually</a>,\nI wanted to organize the directory structure of the project to better fit my\nworkflow.</p>\n<p>Gatsby core automatically turns React components in <strong>src/pages</strong> into pages.\nPrior to this plugin, that functionality was only available to Gatsby core\nas an internal plugin. There was no way to have a different folder\nautomatically create pages from components because the default <strong>src/pages</strong>\npath was hardcoded. The side effect of this behavior\nis that you have a hard time creating folder structures that best fit your needs.\nIf you wanted all your javascript to live in a single folder, you would\nlose the ability to automatically create pages.</p>\n<h1 id=\"the-community-asks-for-a-solution\"><a href=\"#the-community-asks-for-a-solution\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>The community asks for a solution</h1>\n<p>After searching the repo issues for a solution, I found other people\nhaving the same problem and asking for a solution. A user in\n<a href=\"https://github.com/gatsbyjs/gatsby/issues/2424\">#2424</a> wanted to move their\ncomponents into a render folder. Another wanted to keep their Gatsby code\nnear non-Gatsby related code but under a different directory name.</p>\n<p>One <a href=\"https://github.com/gatsbyjs/gatsby/issues/2514\">issue</a> raised how\nuncommon this pattern might be when handing a project over to other\nclients that are less technical. Each issue focused on a valid concern, with\nmany community members in support of a better convention. With this data,\nI set out to determine a solution for this problem.</p>\n<h1 id=\"the-great-pull-request\"><a href=\"#the-great-pull-request\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>The great pull request</h1>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/page-creator-pull-request-0b5687e1426ef803be92c626a6947c8c-e34da.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 786px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 49.916666666666664%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px #ffffff;\"\n        alt=\"Pull request for gatsby plugin page creator\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/page-creator-pull-request-0b5687e1426ef803be92c626a6947c8c-c4266.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/page-creator-pull-request-0b5687e1426ef803be92c626a6947c8c-4fd5b.png 197w,\n/static/page-creator-pull-request-0b5687e1426ef803be92c626a6947c8c-4fc86.png 393w,\n/static/page-creator-pull-request-0b5687e1426ef803be92c626a6947c8c-c4266.png 786w,\n/static/page-creator-pull-request-0b5687e1426ef803be92c626a6947c8c-22348.png 1179w,\n/static/page-creator-pull-request-0b5687e1426ef803be92c626a6947c8c-e34da.png 1200w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 786px) 100vw, 786px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>With the help of Kyle Mathews, he directed me to the location of the\ninternal plugin responsible for the hardcoded behavior. To support the desired\nfunctionality, we would have to extract the internal plugin so\nany project could download the plugin from npm.</p>\n<p>The next step would be to add a path option that takes a directory path string\nto denote the directory of components we want to use for\nautomatic page creation. With a development plan in place, I started\ncoding a solution. After a few days of coding, I opened a pull request to\nadd a <code class=\"language-text\">gatsby-plugin-page-creator</code> to the Gatsby Plugin\nLibrary. After a few weeks of code reviews the\n<a href=\"https://github.com/gatsbyjs/gatsby/pull/4490\">pull request</a> was merged!</p>\n<h1 id=\"how-you-can-use-this-plugin\"><a href=\"#how-you-can-use-this-plugin\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>How you can use this plugin</h1>\n<p>You can find\n<a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/packages/gatsby-plugin-page-creator/?=page-creator\"><code class=\"language-text\">gatsby-plugin-page-creator</code></a>\nin the plugin library. Use <code class=\"language-text\">yarn add gatsby-plugin-page-creator</code> to add this\ninto your project. In <code class=\"language-text\">gatsby-config.js</code>, use a JSON object to use the\nplugin, making sure to add the required path option with your desired directory\npath.</p>\n<p>If you need to designate another location for auto page creation, add another entry of the\nplugin with a different path. You can have unlimited directories responsible for\nauto page creation. The result is you can keep your project well organized without\nhaving to give up on the most powerful out-of-the-box feature.</p>\n<h1 id=\"community-reception\"><a href=\"#community-reception\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Community reception</h1>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/npm-stats-eef874a6e0f66df5adedbebf9eef4e5e-bbbd2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 786px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 39.898348157560356%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px #ffffff;\"\n        alt=\"NPM stats for gatsby plugin page creator\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/npm-stats-eef874a6e0f66df5adedbebf9eef4e5e-c4266.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/npm-stats-eef874a6e0f66df5adedbebf9eef4e5e-4fd5b.png 197w,\n/static/npm-stats-eef874a6e0f66df5adedbebf9eef4e5e-4fc86.png 393w,\n/static/npm-stats-eef874a6e0f66df5adedbebf9eef4e5e-c4266.png 786w,\n/static/npm-stats-eef874a6e0f66df5adedbebf9eef4e5e-22348.png 1179w,\n/static/npm-stats-eef874a6e0f66df5adedbebf9eef4e5e-f35d4.png 1572w,\n/static/npm-stats-eef874a6e0f66df5adedbebf9eef4e5e-1ea43.png 2358w,\n/static/npm-stats-eef874a6e0f66df5adedbebf9eef4e5e-bbbd2.png 3148w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 786px) 100vw, 786px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>This plugin has by far been the most impactful open source contribution I have made\nto date. As of writing, the newly published Gatsby plugin has been\n<a href=\"https://npm-stat.com/charts.html?package=gatsby-plugin-page-creator&#x26;from=2018-06-01&#x26;to=2018-07-18\">downloaded more than 50k+ times</a>\nin less than a month!</p>\n<p>I am happy this plugin is being used by so many developers. What brings me even more joy is that this small contribution will help the Gatsby community continue to deliver an amazing open source tool.</p>\n<h1 id=\"gatsby-manor\"><a href=\"#gatsby-manor\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Gatsby Manor</h1>\n<p><a href=\"https://gatsbymanor.com\">Gatsby Manor</a> builds professional design\nGatsby starters. We make starters to meet your project needs, with new starters\nadded monthly. Can’t find a starter you like? Message us and we’ll\nbuild a starter project for you.</p>","excerpt":"In this article we will talk about a new plugin that lets you auto create\npages from components in any folder within your Gatsby project! We…","timeToRead":4,"fields":{"slug":"/blog/2018-07-07-the-gatsby-plugin-page-creator/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Automatically create pages from components in any directory","excerpt":null,"date":"July 7th 2018","rawDate":"2018-07-07","canonicalLink":null,"publishedAt":null,"tags":["themes","starters","gatsby-manor"],"image":null,"imageAuthor":null,"imageAuthorLink":null,"imageTitle":null,"showImageInArticle":null,"author":{"id":"Steven Natera","bio":"Founder of Gatsby Manor. Site Reliability Engineer. Open source addict. Writer at Hackernoon.","twitter":"@stevennatera","avatar":{"childImageSharp":{"fixed":{"tracedSVG":"data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' width='30' height='30' viewBox='0 0 30 30' version='1'%3e%3crect width='100%25' height='100%25' fill='%23f6f2f8'/%3e%3cpath d='M3 1v1l1 4c1 4 1 4-2 3-2 0-2 0-1 1v2l-1 1h1l1 1c-1 3 2 5 5 3h1c1 1-1 5-2 5l-2 2-2 2c-1 0-2 0-2 2v2h31v-3l-1-2-2-1c-1-1-3-2-2 0l-1 1-3 2h-2l2-2c2-2 1-3-1-2-3 0-3 0-3-7l-1-3-1-1h1c3 0 1-7-2-10l-2-1c0 2-5 2-5 0L7 3 6 6V3c0-3 0-3-1-2H3m7 5v1l1 1c-1 1 0 1 2 1 4 0 4 0 3-2s-5-3-6-1' fill='%23e0d6eb' fill-rule='evenodd'/%3e%3c/svg%3e","width":63,"height":63,"src":"/static/steven-natera-229d66d396a68a479ce7de8dfad6c700-eb2ad.jpg","srcSet":"/static/steven-natera-229d66d396a68a479ce7de8dfad6c700-eb2ad.jpg 1x,\n/static/steven-natera-229d66d396a68a479ce7de8dfad6c700-2d344.jpg 1.5x,\n/static/steven-natera-229d66d396a68a479ce7de8dfad6c700-6dc12.jpg 2x,\n/static/steven-natera-229d66d396a68a479ce7de8dfad6c700-c804e.jpg 3x"}}},"fields":{"slug":"/contributors/steven-natera/"}}}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/blog/2018-07-07-the-gatsby-plugin-page-creator/","prev":{"fields":{"slug":"/blog/2018-06-26-card-sort-results/","package":null,"starterShowcase":null},"frontmatter":{"title":"Presenting the Docs Redesign Card Sort Results","draft":null,"canonicalLink":null,"publishedAt":null,"tags":["documentation"]}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/blog/2018-07-07-graphic-design-class/","package":null,"starterShowcase":null},"frontmatter":{"title":"Learning how to code with Gatsby","draft":null,"canonicalLink":null,"publishedAt":null,"tags":["college","case study","design","getting-started"]}}}}